}}

The '''Shin'nōzuka Kofun''' (小田中親王塚古墳) is a round Kofun and the larger of the two in the Kodanaka Kofun Group. It is one of the largest round mounds in the Hokuriku region and measures approximately 65 meters in diameter and 14 meters in height.

== Kamezuka Kofun ==

{{Infobox ancient site
|name=Kamezuka Kofun
|image=
|location=[[Nakanoto, Ishikawa|Nakanoto]], {{ill|Kashima District, Ishikawa|ja|鹿島郡}}, {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県}}
|coordinates={{coord|36|56|29.33|N|136|52|41.54|E|region:JP-17_type:landmark|display=inline|name=Kamezuka Kofun}}
|type=[[Zenpō-kōhō-fun]] (keyhole-shaped mound)
|size=Total length: 62m<br />Rear height: 8.4m
|built=Unknown
|burial=Unknown
|buried_person=[[Ōirikino-mikoto]] (Imperial Household Historic Site)
|imperial_mausoleum=Associated mound ("Flying Zone I")
|historic_site=Included in the "Shin'nōzuka and Kamezuka Kofun" historic site
}}

The '''Kamezuka Kofun''' (小田中亀塚古墳) is located 40 meters northwest of the Shin'nōzuka Kofun. This zenpō-kōhō-fun measures 62 meters in total length and features a rectangular rear section.

== Cultural Significance ==

Both kofun are notable for their size and historical references, particularly in ancient literature. burial goods such as mirrors and tubular beads found at these sites are indicative of early Kofun-period burial practices.

