'''Kodanaka Kofun Group''' (小田中古墳群) is a {{ill|kofun group|ja|古墳群|1=Kofun cluster|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Nakanoto, Ishikawa|ja|中能登町|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kashima District, Ishikawa|ja|鹿島郡|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県|qq=draft}}. It consists of two Kofuns: the {{ill|Shin'nōzuka Kofun|ja|小田中親王塚古墳|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Kamezuka Kofun|ja|小田中亀塚古墳|qq=draft}}. Although the identities of the interred individuals are unknown, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|qq=draft}} has Historic Site1 the mounds as the "Tomb of Ōirikino-mikoto" (大入杵命墓) and its {{ill|Baizuka|lt=associated mound|ja|陪塚|qq=draft}}. The site has also been Historic Site1 a municipal historic site by Nakanoto Town under the name "Shin'nōzuka and Kamezuka Kofun."

== Overview ==

The Kodanaka Kofun Group is situated in northern Ishikawa Prefecture, at the base of the Ishikurayama Range in the central {{ill|Yuchi Graben|ja|邑知地溝帯|qq=draft}}. This group consists of two early Kofun-period mounds from the late 4th century. The mounds are approximately 40 meters apart{{Sfn|Kodanaka Kofun Group (Heibonsha)|1991}}. The Shin'nōzuka Kofun is referenced in the 7th volume of the {{ill|Heike Monogatari|ja|平家物語|qq=draft}}, where it is described as the "New King's Mound" (新王の塚), suggesting it has been known since ancient times{{Sfn|Mausoleums: Report 66|2015|11=1-23}}.

Both mounds are currently under the management of the Imperial Household Agency, and recent surveys were conducted in 2011–2012 by the {{ill|Archives and Mausolea Department|ja|書陵部|qq=draft}} (Bureau of Mausolea). These mounds were Historic Site1 Imperial tombs in 1875 and were later Historic Site1 municipal historic sites in 1958.

== Historical Timeline ==

* Mentioned as "New King's Mound" in the {{ill|Heike Monogatari|ja|平家物語|qq=draft}}.
* 1704: Referenced in the "Noto Ichiran-ki" with the mention of a shrine at the top of Shin'nōzuka{{Sfn|Mausoleums: Report 66|2015|11=1-23}}.
* 1875: Designated as the "Tomb of Ōirikino-mikoto" by the Ministry of the Imperial Household{{Sfn|Mausoleums: Report 66|2015|11=1-23}}.
* 1958: Designated a municipal historic site by Kashima Town (now Nakanoto Town).

== Shin'nōzuka Kofun ==

